**\\n\\nI’m looking at the inclusion of junit-jupiter-api and wondering if it’s enough. It might not include the necessary engine discovery class template that my test framework requires. The TestClassScanner utilizes LauncherFactory and TestPlan, with the class annotated @ClassTemplate. If the existing test engine from TCK is older, it could mean that our test methods might not execute properly if they rely on this template. I really need to check compatibility to avoid issues.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Troubleshooting JUnit setup**\\n\\nI'm looking at an error related to the current JUnit API being at version 5.9. It seems I need to add `testImplementation 'org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter-api:6.0.0'` and `testRuntimeOnly 'org.junit.jupiter:junit-jupiter-engine:6.0.0'`. I'm also wondering if the JUnit 6 artifact group is indeed `org.junit.jupiter`. Do I need a launcher too? It looks like spring-test might have a platform launcher. I should inspect the POM file, but maybe just adding the engine will be sufficient.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting Gradle configurations**\\n\\nI'm looking into the Gradle configuration for version 6.0.0. It seems the existing launcher might be outdated. I need to figure out if I should include `testRuntimeOnly 'org.junit.platform:junit-platform-launcher:6.0.0'` since it looks like spring-test could depend on it. I should check the source imports and the POM file for dependencies. I can use the cache to find key details, but I’m not running any tests right now. Let’s inspect the Spring-test POM.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_tcCsWPydKkC0sTCcICp7aJRG|fc_0075baf0ccae12af016a28a9c0ca488195a5f9c44cb0ae521f", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -n \"junit\" -C2 ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework/spring-test/7.0.0/*/spring-test-7.0.0.pom | head -80 || true && grep -R \"junit-jupiter\" -n tests/src/org.springframework/spring-test/*/build.gradle"}, "partialJson": 